{
  "doc_id": "10926",
  "text": "Measurements of a real computer system must be made under some processing load. The art of benchmarking has evolved to provide programs that, taken as a whole, are thought to be representative of the processing load seen by the machine in actual use. Benchmarking is still an art, however. Little agreement exists on how to even characterize typical processing loads, much less to create benchmarks that accurately represent these loads. Even representative small-scale processes do not capture or duplicate such important systems-level conditions as process swap overhead and I/O interrupts. For systems with caches, small benchmarks may fit entirely within the cache, exaggerating the performance benefits of such caches [CITATION_1] .",
  "correct_citation": {
